<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="249" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1436,1412,1976]" pageId="10" pageNumber="249">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1519,1544]" pageId="10" pageNumber="249">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Shell small, slightly exceeding 
<quantity box="[699,782,1520,1544]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="249" unit="mm" value="10.0">10 mm</quantity>
in length, narrowly fusiform, with high spire and long, narrow, slightly abaxially recurved siphonal canal. Protoconch multispiral (fossil species) or paucispiral, bulbous (Recent species). Multispiral protoconchs with more than 
<number box="[807,821,1592,1616]" pageId="10" pageNumber="249" value="4.0">4</number>
whorls, last whorls with sharp, opisthocyrt, axial ribs. Spiral sculpture of strong, broadly spaced, narrow spiral cords, intersected by prominent axial ribs, often forming beads on intersections. Cords more closely spaced on canal. Aperture narrow, columella smooth. Outer lip with shallow sinus above periphery in profile.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1436,1412,1976]" pageId="10" pageNumber="249">Operculum absent. Rachidian teeth of the radula with broad, deeply notched, anterior base and large cusp emanating from posterior margin, sometimes with additional lateral serration; lateral teeth high but narrow, pointed, triangular, and scoop-shaped, with small denticles on inner side.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="250" pageId="10" pageNumber="249" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1436,1412,1976]" pageId="10" pageNumber="249">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1844,1869]" pageId="10" pageNumber="249">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[323,398,1845,1868]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rutaceae" genus="Hortia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="10" pageNumber="249" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[323,398,1845,1868]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="249">Hortia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was originally described in the family 
<taxonomicName box="[844,943,1844,1869]" class="Gastropoda" family="Turridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="10" pageNumber="249" phylum="Mollusca" rank="family">Turridae</taxonomicName>
. It is most similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[1186,1323,1844,1869]" class="Gastropoda" family="Turridae" genus="Vaughanites" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="10" pageNumber="249" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1186,1323,1844,1869]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="249">Vaughanites</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, differing by a generally shorter, abaxially recurved canal, and by the absence of columellar plaits. It also differs from 
<emphasis box="[151,294,1917,1940]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="249">Pyramimitra</emphasis>
in having narrower axial ribs (rather than varices) and a longer siphonal canal, and the absence of columellar plaits.
</paragraph>
